Art: The creation of beautiful or significant things
A superior skill that you can learn by study and practice and observation
Church: A place for public (especially Christian) worship
A service conducted in a house of worship
One of the groups of Christians who have their own beliefs and forms of worship
The body of people who attend or belong to a particular local church
Cabinet: A storage compartment for clothes and valuables; usually it has a lock
Persons appointed by a head of state to head executive departments of government and act as official advisers
People: Any group of human beings (men or women or children) collectively
The body of citizens of a state or country
Bonus: An additional payment (or other remuneration) to employees as a means of increasing output
Basket: A container that is usually woven and has handles
Horizontal circular metal hoop supporting a net through which players try to throw the basketball
History: A record or narrative description of past events
All that is remembered of the past as preserved in writing; a body of knowledge
The continuum of events occurring in succession leading from the past to the present and even into the future
The discipline that records and interprets past events involving human beings
World: The 3rd planet from the sun; the planet we live on
Map: A diagrammatic representation of the earth's surface (or part of it)
Aircraft: Any machine supported for flight in the air by buoyancy or by the dynamic action of air on its surfaces, especially powered airplanes, gliders, and helicopters.
Discipline: Training to act in accordance with rules; drill
Activity, exercise, or a regimen that develops or improves a skill; training
Challenge: A call or summons to engage in any contest, as of skill, strength, etc.
Something that by its nature or character serves as a call to battle, contest, special effort, etc.
